  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Personification is figurative language that gives human qualities to nonhuman things — objects, animals, abstractions, or natural forces. \u0026ldquo;The wind whispered,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;the market punished investors,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;justice is blind.\u0026rdquo; The nonhuman thing is described as if it could act, feel, perceive, or intend.\nPersonification works because human minds are wired to understand agency. When a writer says \u0026ldquo;the deadline loomed,\u0026rdquo; the reader understands the deadline as a threatening presence — not literally alive but felt as if it were. This is not imprecision; it is compression. \u0026ldquo;The deadline loomed\u0026rdquo; communicates urgency, anxiety, and threat in three words that a literal description would need a paragraph to match.\n",
  "name": "Personification",
